  "prompt": "Solutions accepted in HackerRank sometimes appear to be not appropriate. Should I follow them or do it in a correct way?",
  "response": "When dealing with coding challenges on platforms like HackerRank, it's important to prioritize correct and efficient solutions over merely accepted ones. Here are a few steps to ensure you are on the right track:\n\n1. **Understand the Problem Statement:** Make sure you fully understand the requirements and constraints of the problem. Sometimes solutions that appear to work may not cover all edge cases or may not be efficient.\n\n2. **Analyze Accepted Solutions:** While some solutions may be accepted, they might not be the best in terms of readability, efficiency, or correctness. Use them as a learning tool to understand different approaches but critically evaluate them.\n\n3. **Research Best Practices:** Look up best practices for coding and algorithms. Many resources and communities such as Stack Overflow, GeeksforGeeks, and official documentation can provide insights into optimal ways to solve problems.\n\n4. **Test Your Solutions Thoroughly:** Ensure your solution works for all possible edge cases and input sizes. Writing test cases can help validate your approach.\n\n5. **Strive for Efficiency:** Consider the time and space complexity of your solution. Aim for an efficient solution, especially for problems with large input sizes.\n\n6. **Code Readability:** Write clean, readable, and maintainable code. This not only helps others understand your solution but also helps you debug and improve your own code.\n\n7. **Continuous Learning:** Keep learning and improving your skills. Engage with coding communities, take online courses, and practice regularly.\n\nIn summary, while accepted solutions can provide valuable insights, you should aim to solve problems correctly and efficiently. This approach will improve your coding skills and prepare you for real-world scenarios where correctness and efficiency are paramount.",
